Find $a+b+c$, given that $x+y\neq -1$ and  \begin{align*}
ax+by+c&=x+7,\\
a+bx+cy&=2x+6y,\\
ay+b+cx&=4x+y.
\end{align*}

inference:
Adding the three equations, we get \begin{align*}
(a+b+c)x+(a+b+c)y+(a+b+c)&=7x+8y+c.
\end{align*} This simplifies to \[(a+b+c)(x+y+1)=7x+8y+c.\]Since $x+y \neq -1$, we can divide both sides by $x+y+1$, giving \[a+b+c=\frac{7x+8y+c}{x+y+1}.\]To get rid of the $x$ and $y$ terms, we can set $x=1$ and $y=0$. Then our equation becomes \[a+b+c=\frac{7+c}{2}.\]Solving for $a+b+c$, we get $a+b+c=\boxed{7}$.  I hope it is correct.

ground_truth:
Since these equations look symmetric, at least on the left-hand side, we add all three together.  This gives us  \begin{align*}
&a(x+1+y)+b(y+x+1)+c(1+y+x)\\
&\qquad\qquad=x+7+2x+6y+4x+y.
\end{align*} We then factor out $(1+x+y)$ on the left and simplify the right side to get \begin{align*}
(1+x+y)(a+b+c)&=7x+7y+7, \text{ so}\\
(1+x+y)(a+b+c)&=7(1+x+y).
\end{align*}

Since $x+y\neq -1$, we know $x+y+1\neq 0$, so we can divide both sides by that term and find that $a+b+c=\boxed{7}$.

